To implement a "Shop by Size" filter page and make sure it properly displays your products and allows for size filtering, here’s an updated approach.

It looks like you're trying to list products that have a `Size` option and display them dynamically. To make this work with the `Shopify Search & Discovery` app filters and Liquid, we need to adjust the code to properly iterate through the products and their variants.

Here's how you can structure your Liquid template code to display products with size filtering.

### 1. Updated Liquid Code to Display Products by Size

```liquid
{% if collection.title == 'Shop by Size' %}
  <div class="custom-size-filter">
    <h2>Filter by Size</h2>

    <!-- List all size options available in the collection -->
    {% assign size_options = '' %}
    {% for product in collection.products %}
      {% for variant in product.variants %}
        {% if variant.option1 == 'Size' %}
          {% assign size_options = size_options | append: variant.option1 %}
        {% endif %}
      {% endfor %}
    {% endfor %}

    <!-- Create buttons for size filter -->
    {% assign size_options = size_options | split: ',' | uniq %}
    {% for size in size_options %}
      <button class="size-filter-btn" data-size="{{ size }}">{{ size }}</button>
    {% endfor %}
  </div>

  <!-- Display products based on selected size -->
  <div class="products-list">
    {% for product in collection.products %}
      <div class="product-item">
        <h3>{{ product.title }}</h3>
        <p>Available sizes: 
          {% for variant in product.variants %}
            {{ variant.option1 }}{% unless forloop.last %}, {% endunless %}
          {% endfor %}
        </p>
        <a href="{{ product.url }}">View Product</a>
      </div>
    {% endfor %}
  </div>
{% else %}
  <!-- Default code for other collections -->
{% endif %}
```

### 2. Explanation of the Code
1. **Filter by Size Options**:
   - The code loops through all the products in the "Shop by Size" collection.
   - It finds any product variants with the "Size" option and collects the available sizes.
   - It creates a button for each unique size value, which can be styled later with CSS.

2. **Displaying Products**:
   - The code displays each product in the collection.
   - It shows the available sizes for each product.

3. **Size Filter Buttons**:
   - The buttons are currently just displayed without functionality. To make them interactive, you’ll need to add some JavaScript to filter the displayed products based on the selected size (optional depending on what interactivity you want).

### 3. Styling (Optional)
If you want to style the size filter buttons, you can use CSS like this:

```css
.size-filter-btn {
  display: inline-block;
  margin: 5px;
  padding: 10px;
  background-color: #0073aa;
  color: #fff;
  border: none;
  cursor: pointer;
}
.size-filter-btn:hover {
  background-color: #005f8c;
}
```

### 4. JavaScript for Size Filtering (Optional)
If you want users to be able to filter products on the page by clicking a size, you can implement some JavaScript to handle this. Here’s a simple example using vanilla JavaScript:

```html
<script>
  document.querySelectorAll('.size-filter-btn').forEach(button => {
    button.addEventListener('click', function() {
      const selectedSize = this.dataset.size;

      document.querySelectorAll('.product-item').forEach(item => {
        const availableSizes = item.querySelector('p').textContent;

        if (availableSizes.includes(selectedSize)) {
          item.style.display = 'block';
        } else {
          item.style.display = 'none';
        }
      });
    });
  });
</script>
```

### 5. Final Notes
- **Product Collection**: This solution assumes your **Shop by Size** collection includes all your products. If you only want to display a subset, adjust your collection conditions.
- **Size Filter**: The size filtering logic here is basic. If you want a more advanced filter (e.g., handling multiple sizes at once), you’ll need to modify the JavaScript accordingly.

This should give you a working "Shop by Size" page where products are displayed, and users can filter by size!

You're correct that Shopify's **Search & Discovery** app provides size filtering as a dropdown, which lists all available sizes. Unfortunately, the default filter behavior in most Shopify themes doesn't allow for advanced customizations such as a detailed "size filter section" with individual buttons or advanced styling options by default. It limits the filter to a dropdown or basic checkbox list for available sizes.

### Possible Approaches to Customize the Size Filter Display

If you want more control over how the size filter is displayed, such as showing individual buttons for each size instead of a dropdown, you can try the following workarounds:

### 1. Use the **"Filter Buttons"** Instead of a Dropdown
To customize the appearance of the size filter (like using buttons instead of a dropdown), you'll need to modify your theme’s Liquid files and create custom JavaScript to interact with the Shopify filter system.

You can display size filter buttons that users can click to trigger the corresponding filter. Here’s a simplified example:

#### Example Code for Filter Buttons
In your `collection-template.liquid` or `collection.liquid` file, modify it to render buttons for each available size.

```liquid
{% if collection.title == 'Shop by Size' %}
  <div class="custom-size-filter">
    <p>Filter by Size:</p>
    <div class="size-buttons">
      {% for option in collection.all_products %}
        {% assign size_options = option.options_with_values['Size'] %}
        {% for size in size_options %}
          <button class="size-filter-button" data-size="{{ size }}">
            {{ size }}
          </button>
        {% endfor %}
      {% endfor %}
    </div>
  </div>
{% endif %}
```

You can style this using CSS to make them appear as buttons, and then use JavaScript to trigger the filtering action.

### 2. Custom JavaScript for Filtering
To make the buttons functional, you will need JavaScript to listen for clicks on the size buttons and apply the corresponding Shopify filter.

Here’s an example of how to apply the size filter when a button is clicked:

```javascript
document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', function() {
  const sizeButtons = document.querySelectorAll('.size-filter-button');

  sizeButtons.forEach(button => {
    button.addEventListener('click', function() {
      const selectedSize = this.getAttribute('data-size');
      // Update the URL to trigger the size filter
      const filterUrl = new URL(window.location);
      filterUrl.searchParams.set('filter.v.option.size', selectedSize);
      window.location = filterUrl;
    });
  });
});
```

This script captures the click event on each button, gets the size from the `data-size` attribute, and updates the page URL with the Shopify size filter parameter.

### 3. Using a Third-Party App
If coding isn’t the desired approach, you might consider a third-party **filter app** for Shopify, like:
- **Boost Product Filter & Search**: Allows much more customization, such as displaying filters in button form, multi-selection, etc.
- **Product Filter & Search by Globo**: Another app with similar capabilities for more advanced filtering displays.

These apps offer advanced filtering capabilities and more control over the user interface, including the ability to display size filters as buttons or in other custom formats.

### Conclusion
The default Shopify size filter via Search & Discovery is somewhat limited (dropdown or checkbox list). If you need something more visually dynamic, like buttons for sizes, you'll either need to customize the theme with Liquid, JavaScript, and CSS, or use a third-party app to achieve the level of control you're seeking.

